French President Emmanuel Macron hit on the issues of climate change, nationalism, trade and the 2015 Iran nuclear deal in his speech to a joint session of US Congress, calling on the United States to engage more with the world. After what has been seen as a friendly state visit to Washington, Macron's speech laid out a view of global leadership starkly different from US President Donald Trump's "America First." What Macron said "We have disagreements between the United States and France. It may happen, like in all families," Macron said. Read more:  Opinion: Bravo Emmanuel Macron! Macron urged a collective approach to the environment and economic growth: "With business leaders and local communities, let us work together in order to make our planet great again and create new jobs and new opportunities while safeguarding our Earth. And I'm sure one day, the United States would come back and join the Paris agreement." Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
